{"title_page": "OneWeb", "text_new": "{{short description|Global communications company}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name          = OneWeb\n| logo          = OneWeb Logo.png\n| logo_size     = 250px\n\n| type          = Private\n| industry      = [[Satellite Internet access]]\n| fate          = Active, chapter 11 bankruptcy protection\n| predecessor   = WorldVu Satellites\n| successor     = <!-- or: | successors = -->\n| founded       = 2012 <!-- if known: {{Start date and age|DD|MM|YYYY}} in [[city]], state, country -->\n| founder       = <!-- or: | founders = -->\n| defunct       = <!-- {{End date|DD|MM|YYYY}} -->\n| location      = [[London]], [[England]], UK <ref name=pr-20180308>{{cite news|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/oneweb-finalizes-executive-team-appointments-leading-up-to-the-launch-of-global-constellation-and-services-300610596.html|title=OneWeb Finalizes Executive Team Appointments Leading Up to the Launch of Global Constellation and Services|agency=[[PR Newswire]]|author=OneWeb|date=8 March 2018|access-date=22 April 2019}}</ref><br>[[McLean, Virginia]], United States\n| area_served   = <!-- or: | areas_served = -->\n| key_people    = {{Unbulleted list|[[Adri\u00e1n Steckel]]|[[CEO]]}}\n| products      = \n| owner         = <!-- or: | owners = -->\n| num_employees = 531 <ref name=sn20200327/>\n| num_employees_year = February 2020 <!-- Year of num_employees data (if known) -->\n| parent        = \n| subsid        = [[OneWeb Satellites]] <!-- OneWeb Satellites is a JV formed with Airbus Defence and Space to mfg the HVLC satellites-->\n| website       = {{URL|oneweb.world/}}\n}}\n'''OneWeb''' is a global communications company founded by [[Greg Wyler]]. The company is headquartered in [[London]], United Kingdom and [[McLean, Virginia]], United States <ref name=\"pr-20180308\"/><ref name=\"govuk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/18m-for-oneweb-satellite-constellation-to-deliver-global-communications|title=\u00a318m for OneWeb satellite constellation to deliver global communications|publisher=[[UK Space Agency]]|date=2019-02-18}}</ref> with offices in California,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-oneweb-softbank-idUSKBN14818O|title=SoftBank to invest $1 billion in U.S. venture OneWeb as part of $50 billion pledge|publisher=[[Reuters]]|last=Yamazaki|first=Makiko|date=19 December 2016|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> as well as a satellite manufacturing facility in Florida \u2014 OneWeb Satellites \u2014 that is a joint venture with [[Airbus Defence and Space]]. The company was formerly known as WorldVu Satellites.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spacenews.com/virgin-qualcomm-invest-in-global-satellite-internet-plan/|title=Virgin, Qualcomm Invest in OneWeb Satellite Internet Venture|publisher=[[Spacenews.com]]|date=15 January 2015|access-date=15 February 2018|last=de Selding |first= Peter B.}}</ref><ref name=\"prnewswire\">{{cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/oneweb-announces-plans-to-launch-a-new-satellite-constellation-to-bring-high-speed-internet-to-underserved-areas-around-the-world-288708881.html|title=OneWeb Announces Plans to Launch a New Satellite Constellation to Bring High-Speed Internet to Underserved Areas Around the World|publisher=[[PR Newswire]]|date=15 January 2015|accessdate=15 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nOneWeb commenced launches of the [[OneWeb satellite constellation]], a network of more than 650 [[low Earth orbit]] [[Miniaturized satellite#Microsatellites|satellites]], in February 2019,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.space.com/arianespace-oneweb-satellites-launch-webcast.html|title=Soyuz Rocket Will Launch the 1st OneWeb Satellites Today: Watch It Live!|last=Hanneke|first=Weitering|date=2019-02-27|website=[[Space.com]]|language=en|access-date=2019-02-27}}</ref> and by March 2020, had launched 74 of the planned 648 satellites in the initial constellation.\n\nOneWeb's goal was to provide [[Satellite internet constellation|internet services]] to \"everyone, everywhere\" delivering internet connections to rural and remote places as well as to a range of markets.\n\nOneWeb filed for [[bankruptcy]] on 27 March 2020, following a [[liquidity crisis|cash crunch]] amidst difficulties raising capital to complete the build and deployment of the remaining 90% of the network. The company had already laid off approximately 85% of its 531 employees, but said it will maintain satellite operational capabilities while the court restructures it and new owners for the constellation are sought.<ref name=sn20200327/><ref name=wired-bankrupt>{{cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/story/spacex-competitor-oneweb-is-reportedly-bankrupt|title=SpaceX Competitor OneWeb Is Reportedly Bankrupt |date=27 March 2020|access-date=28 March 2020|website=Wired|last=Oberhaus|first=Daniel}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe company was founded in 2012 under the name WorldVu,<ref name=\"prnewswire\"/> based in Britain's [[Channel Islands]].<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://spacenews.com/41755worldvu-a-satellite-startup-aiming-to-provide-global-internet/|title=WorldVu, a Satellite Startup Aiming To Provide Global Internet Connectivity, Continues To Grow Absent Clear Google Relationship|publisher=[[Spacenews.com]]|date=3 September 2014|access-date=15 February 2018|last=de Selding|first=Peter B.}}</ref> \n\nIn 2015, OneWeb secured US$500 million in funding, and agreed to purchase certain future launch services, from existing aerospace industry companies [[Arianespace]] and [[Virgin Galactic]].<ref name=nbc20150625>{{cite news|title=OneWeb Wins US$500 Million in Backing for Internet Satellite Network|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/science/space/oneweb-wins-500-million-backing-internet-satellite-network-n381691|work=NBC News|date=2015-06-25|access-date=2016-02-08|last=Boyle|first=Alan}}</ref><ref name=sn20140530>{{Cite news|title=Google-backed Global Broadband Venture Secures Spectrum for Satellite Network |url=http://spacenews.com/40736google-backed-global-broadband-venture-secures-spectrum-for-satellite/|work=[[SpaceNews]]|date=2014-05-30|access-date=2016-02-08|language=en-US|last=de Selding|first=Peter B.}}</ref> In June 2015, OneWeb also entered into a deal with [[Airbus Defence and Space]] for the construction of its broadband Internet satellites after a competition among U.S. and European manufacturers.<ref>{{Cite web|title=OneWeb selects Airbus to build 900 Internet satellites {{!}} Spaceflight Now|url=http://spaceflightnow.com/2015/06/15/oneweb-selects-airbus-to-build-900-internet-satellites/|access-date=2016-02-08|first=Stephen|last=Clark}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, one year after the initial announcement, OneWeb stated they were on schedule.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spacenews.com/one-year-after-kickoff-oneweb-says-its-700-satellite-constellation-is-on-schedule/|title=One year after kickoff, OneWeb says its 700-satellite constellation is on schedule|date=6 July 2016|last=de Selding|first=Peter B.|access-date=28 March 2020|website=SpaceNews}}</ref> In December 2016, OneWeb raised US$1 billion from [[SoftBank Group|SoftBank Group Corp.]] and US$200 million from existing investors.<ref name=sn201702/><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/oneweb-softbank/softbank-to-invest-1-billion-in-u-s-satellite-venture-oneweb-idUSL4N1EE3I6|title=SoftBank to invest $1 billion in U.S. satellite venture OneWeb|last=Weir |first=Keith|website=Reuters|access-date=2016-12-19}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, OneWeb announced that it expected to sell all of its capacity by launch time, yet the only announced capacity sold was for a joint [[Gogo Inflight Internet|Gogo]] and [[Intelsat]] venture. Wyler announced he was considering nearly quadrupling the size of the satellite constellation by adding 1972 additional satellites that it has priority rights to.<ref name=sn201702>{{cite web |url=https://spacenews.com/oneweb-weighing-2000-more-satellites/|title=OneWeb weighing 2,000 more satellites - SpaceNews.com|date=24 February 2017|publisher=SpaceNews|access-date=23 April 2018|last=Pultarova |first=Tereza}}</ref> With the original capital raise of US$500 million in 2015, plus the US$1 billion investment of SoftBank in 2016, previous \"investors committed to an additional US$200 million, bringing OneWeb's total capital raised to US$1.7 billion\".<ref name=sn201702/> A [[merger]] arrangement with [[Intelsat]] that had been in negotiations during May 2017 collapsed in June and did not go forward.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spacenews.com/oneweb-says-no-steam-lost-despite-intelsat-merger-unravelling/|title=OneWeb says no steam lost despite Intelsat merger unravelling - SpaceNews.com|date=1 June 2017 |publisher=SpaceNews|access-date=23 April 2018|last=Henry|first=Caleb}}</ref>\n\n[[File:OneWeb satellite manufacturing facility, Merritt Island, Florida, 2019 01.jpg|thumb|left|upright=2|OneWeb satellite manufacturing facility in Merritt Island, Florida]]\n\nBy 2019, OneWeb had formed a [[joint venture]] \u2014 '''OneWeb Satellites'''<!-- bolded per [[WP:MOSBOLD]] as a redirect target --> \u2014 with the European company [[Airbus Defence and Space]] in order to manufacturer its satellites in higher volume and at lower cost than any satellites previously built by Airbus. A manufacturing facility was built in [[Merritt Island, Florida]]. Initial satellite production at the new facility began in mid-2019 and by January 2020, the factory reached the target production rate of two satellites per day.<ref name=sn20200206>{{cite news|url=https://spacenews.com/oneweb-plans-april-launch-break-to-tweak-satellite-design/|title=OneWeb plans April launch break to tweak satellite design|work=[[SpaceNews]]|last=Henry|first=Caleb|date=6 February 2020|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 February 2019, OneWeb successfully launched its first six satellites into low Earth orbit from the [[Centre Spatial Guyanais]] in [[French Guiana]] using a [[Soyuz-2]] rocket.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.oneweb.world/newsroom/oneweb-makes-history-as-first-launch-mission-is-a-success|title=OneWeb makes history as first launch mission is a success|date=2019-02-28|work=OneWeb|access-date=2019-02-28|language=en|archive-date=15 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190515095707/https://www.oneweb.world/newsroom/oneweb-makes-history-as-first-launch-mission-is-a-success|url-status=dead}}</ref> The same day OneWeb announced that it signed its first two client agreements marking the beginning of its commercialization.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oneweb.world/newsroom/oneweb-announces-first-two-client-agreements-start-of-commercial-network-commercialisation|title=OneWeb Announces First Two Client Agreements - Start of Commercial Network Commercialisation|date=2019-02-27|work=OneWeb |access-date=2019-02-27|language=en|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512165012/https://www.oneweb.world/newsroom/oneweb-announces-first-two-client-agreements-start-of-commercial-network-commercialisation|archive-date=12 May 2019}}</ref> On 18 March 2019, OneWeb announced it had secured $1.25 billion in funding following a successful first launch. The funding was from existing investors SoftBank and Qualcomm, as well as [[Grupo Salinas]] and the [[Government of Rwanda]].<ref name=bloomberg20190318>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-03-18/oneweb-raises-fresh-1-25-billion-for-internet-system-from-space?|title=OneWeb Raises Fresh $1.25 Billion for Internet System From Space|work=[[Bloomberg News]]|date=18 March 2019|access-date=21 March 2020|last=Vance|first=Ashlee}}</ref>\n\nBy August 2019, the company had 6 of its satellites broadcasting at the right frequencies for 90 days, meeting the \"use-it-or-lose-it\" spectrum conditions set by the [[United Nations]]' [[International Telecommunication Union]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-08-07/oneweb-claims-a-win-in-internet-space-race-with-musk-and-bezos?srnd=markets-vp|title=OneWeb Claims a Win in Internet Space Race Against Musk and Bezos|last=Seal|first=Thomas|date=7 August 2019|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-12}}</ref> This secured the vital rights OneWeb needed to operate its global satellite broadband network.<ref name=\":1\"/>\n\nIn February and March 2020, the company launched an additional 68 satellites to orbit, stating that it would slow down for a minor design modification to be made before planning to launch again in May.<ref name=sn20200206/>\n\nIn March 2020, during the [[2019\u201320_coronavirus_pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]] and [[2020 stock market crash|market turmoil]], OneWeb found themselves in a [[Liquidity crisis|cash crunch]] and is considering [[bankruptcy|bankruptcy court protection]] even as it is looking for out-of-court alternatives to funding ongoing operations.<ref name=bloomberglaw20200319>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-19/softbank-s-oneweb-is-said-to-mull-bankruptcy-as-cash-dwindles|title= SoftBank's OneWeb to Consider Bankruptcy as Cash Dwindles|work=Bloomberg Technology|last=Ronalds-Hannon|first=Eliza|date=19 March 2020|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> By the time of the bankruptcy filing, the company had reduced its workforce from 531 employees down to 74.<ref>{{cite web|title=Motion to Authorize / Debtors' Motion for (A) Interim and Final Authority to (I) Pay Prepetition Wages, Salaries, and Other Compensation and Benefits, (II) Maintain Employee Benefit Programs, and (B) Certain Related Relief filed by Dennis F. Dunne on behalf of OneWeb Global Limited|url=https://www.bankruptcyobserver.com/document/ONEWEB-GLOBAL/9|work=BankruptcyObserver.com |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The effect on the previously planned ten launches in 2020 was not publicly discussed.<ref name=ars20200323>{{cite news|url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2020/03/oneweb-launches-new-satellites-amid-questions-about-its-fiscal-health/|title=OneWeb Says It Will Have To Cut Workers Amid Economic Crisis|work=Ars technica|last=Berger|first=Eric|date=23 March 2020|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn March 27, 2020, OneWeb Global Limited and 18 affiliates all filed bankruptcy in the [[United States Bankruptcy Court for the Southern District of New York]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://spaceflightnow.com/2020/03/30/oneweb-files-for-bankruptcy/|date=30 March 2020|last=Clark|first=Stephen|access-date=30 March 2020|work=Spaceflight Now|title=OneWeb files for bankruptcy}}</ref><ref name=bankobs20200327/><ref name=wired-bankrupt/> The company blamed the [[2019\u201320_coronavirus_pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]], but they need to raise an additional several billion dollars of capital after development and early testing was always a part of the plan, and the high-cost structure of OneWeb's [[Space launch market competition|contracted launches]] and satellites relative to the market size and other emerging competition had been known for some time, and was thought to be challenging well prior to the emergence of the pandemic.<ref name=sn20200327>{{cite news|url=https://spacenews.com/oneweb-files-for-chapter-11-bankruptcy/|title=OneWeb files for Chapter 11 bankruptcy|work=[[SpaceNews]]|last=Henry|first=Caleb|date=27 March 2020|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> The primary case is identified as case number 20-22437.<ref name=bankobs20200327>{{cite web|title=Bankruptcy of OneWeb Global Limited|url=https://www.bankruptcyobserver.com/bankruptcy-case/ONEWEB-GLOBAL|work=BankruptcyObserver.com|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> OneWeb Satellites, the joint venture between OneWeb and Airbus Defence to build the satellites, says they have done temporary furloughs due to the Coronavirus pandemic but that they are not due to the OneWeb bankruptcy filing.<ref>{{cite tweet |last=Foust |first=Jeff|author-link=Jeff Foust |user=jeff_foust |number=1244632083689078785 |date=30 March 2020 |title=OneWeb Satellites... has implemented 'temporary furloughs' of staff, but says that is due to COVID-19 and not OneWeb's Ch. 11 bankruptcy filing. |access-date=30 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Satellites ==\n[[File:KSC-20170316-PH KLS01 0007~orig.jpg|thumb|Model of a OneWeb satellite]]\n{{main|OneWeb satellite constellation}}\nIn 2016, OneWeb planned for a launch cadence of 30-36 satellites a month <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spacenews.com/leo-constellation-operators-oneweb-iridium-announce-collaboration/|title=LEO constellation operators OneWeb, Iridium announce collaboration|date=2019-09-17|website=SpaceNews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-20|last=Henry|first=Caleb}}</ref> to create an initial constellation of 650 satellites. The satellites operate in Low Earth Orbit (LEO). OneWeb chose an altitude of 1200 km for its satellites because there is a minimum existing population of satellites and [[space debris|debris]] at that altitude.<ref name=\":2\"/>\n\nLike existing LEO based communications satellite constellations, OneWeb's satellites are closer to Earth and will, therefore, provide much lower transmission delays than geostationary satellite broadband services<ref name=\":3\"/>. As late as January 2020, OneWeb was still planning to provide 10 times the bandwidth and one-tenth of the latency of existing geostationary satellites.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.computerweekly.com/feature/Norways-autonomous-ships-point-to-new-horizons|title=Norway's autonomous ships point to new horizons|website=ComputerWeekly.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-02 |date=29 May 2019|last=Mathieson|first=SA}}</ref>\n\nOneWeb's factory in Exploration Park on [[Merritt Island, Florida]] opened in July 2019, just outside the gates of NASA's Kennedy Space Center.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://spaceflightnow.com/2020/03/17/soyuz-launch-preps-in-kazakhstan-proceeding-despite-travel-restrictions/|title=Soyuz launch preps in Kazakhstan proceed despite travel restrictions|access-date=18 March 2020|date=17 March 2020|last=Clark|first=Stephen|website=Spaceflight Now}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/orlando/news/2019/07/29/oneweb-satellites-opens-85m-production-facility-in.html|title=OneWeb Satellite Opens 85m Production Facility|last=Saleh|first=Malak|date=29 July 2019|website=Orlando Business Journal|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref> The factory is a joint venture with [[Airbus]] and has a production capacity of two satellites a day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thisismoney.co.uk/money/markets/article-7344829/Adrian-Steckel-rocketman-wholl-launch-34-satellites-MONTH.html|title=Adrian Steckel: The rocketman who'll launch 34 satellites every MONTH|last=Nimmo|first=Jamie|date=2019-08-10|website=Mail Online|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref> The satellites will be programmed to detect the end of their life span after 5-7 years in orbit, and deorbit themselves from space and so that they burn up in the atmosphere as they [[atmospheric reentry|descend towards Earth]].<ref name=\":4\"/>\n\n== Responsible space ==\nIn June 2019, OneWeb rolled out its initiative Responsible Space to outline the specific approaches it plans to take to promote sustainability and safe operations in space.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web |url=https://spacenews.com/can-satellite-megaconstellations-be-responsible-users-of-space/|title=Can satellite megaconstellations be responsible users of space?|date=2019-09-03|website=SpaceNews.com |language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-22|last=Foust|first=Jeff}}</ref> Responsible Space covers design and operational practices, including disposal of a satellite within 5 years of the end of its mission; developing an \"ecosystem\" within the space industry that supports sustainability; and collaboration with other space operators.<ref name=\":2\"/>&nbsp;As one example, OneWeb plans to include a grapple fixture on its satellites so that a third-party satellite could grab it and tug it out of orbit, should the satellite prove non-responsive.<ref name=\":2\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Portal|Spaceflight}}\n* {{Official website|oneweb.world}}\n\n[[Category:Satellite Internet access]]\n[[Category:Communications satellite operators]]\n[[Category:Aerospace companies]]\n[[Category:Satellite telephony]]\n[[Category:2012 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British companies established in 2012]]\n[[Category:British brands]]\n[[Category:Companies based in London]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 2012]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Arlington County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Companies that filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy in 2020]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Global communications company}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name          = OneWeb\n| logo          = OneWeb Logo.png\n| logo_size     = 250px\n\n| type          = Private\n| industry      = [[Satellite Internet access]]\n| fate          = Active, chapter 11 bankruptcy protection\n| predecessor   = WorldVu Satellites\n| successor     = <!-- or: | successors = -->\n| founded       = 2012 <!-- if known: {{Start date and age|DD|MM|YYYY}} in [[city]], state, country -->\n| founder       = <!-- or: | founders = -->\n| defunct       = <!-- {{End date|DD|MM|YYYY}} -->\n| location      = [[London]], [[England]], UK <ref name=pr-20180308>{{cite news|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/oneweb-finalizes-executive-team-appointments-leading-up-to-the-launch-of-global-constellation-and-services-300610596.html|title=OneWeb Finalizes Executive Team Appointments Leading Up to the Launch of Global Constellation and Services|agency=[[PR Newswire]]|author=OneWeb|date=8 March 2018|access-date=22 April 2019}}</ref><br>[[McLean, Virginia]], United States\n| area_served   = <!-- or: | areas_served = -->\n| key_people    = {{Unbulleted list|[[Adri\u00e1n Steckel]]|[[CEO]]}}\n| products      = \n| owner         = <!-- or: | owners = -->\n| num_employees = 531 <ref name=sn20200327/>\n| num_employees_year = February 2020 <!-- Year of num_employees data (if known) -->\n| parent        = \n| subsid        = [[OneWeb Satellites]] <!-- OneWeb Satellites is a JV formed with Airbus Defence and Space to mfg the HVLC satellites-->\n| website       = {{URL|oneweb.world/}}\n}}\n'''OneWeb''' is a global communications company founded by [[Greg Wyler]]. The company is headquartered in [[London]], United Kingdom and [[McLean, Virginia]], United States <ref name=\"pr-20180308\"/><ref name=\"govuk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/18m-for-oneweb-satellite-constellation-to-deliver-global-communications|title=\u00a318m for OneWeb satellite constellation to deliver global communications|publisher=[[UK Space Agency]]|date=2019-02-18}}</ref> with offices in California,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-oneweb-softbank-idUSKBN14818O|title=SoftBank to invest $1 billion in U.S. venture OneWeb as part of $50 billion pledge|publisher=[[Reuters]]|last=Yamazaki|first=Makiko|date=19 December 2016|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> as well as a satellite manufacturing facility in Florida \u2014 OneWeb Satellites \u2014 that is a joint venture with [[Airbus Defence and Space]]. The company was formerly known as WorldVu Satellites.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spacenews.com/virgin-qualcomm-invest-in-global-satellite-internet-plan/|title=Virgin, Qualcomm Invest in OneWeb Satellite Internet Venture|publisher=[[Spacenews.com]]|date=15 January 2015|access-date=15 February 2018|last=de Selding |first= Peter B.}}</ref><ref name=\"prnewswire\">{{cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/oneweb-announces-plans-to-launch-a-new-satellite-constellation-to-bring-high-speed-internet-to-underserved-areas-around-the-world-288708881.html|title=OneWeb Announces Plans to Launch a New Satellite Constellation to Bring High-Speed Internet to Underserved Areas Around the World|publisher=[[PR Newswire]]|date=15 January 2015|accessdate=15 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nOneWeb commenced launches of the [[OneWeb satellite constellation]], a network of more than 650 [[low Earth orbit]] [[Miniaturized satellite#Microsatellites|satellites]], in February 2019,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.space.com/arianespace-oneweb-satellites-launch-webcast.html|title=Soyuz Rocket Will Launch the 1st OneWeb Satellites Today: Watch It Live!|last=Hanneke|first=Weitering|date=2019-02-27|website=[[Space.com]]|language=en|access-date=2019-02-27}}</ref> and by March 2020, had launched 74 of the planned 648 satellites in the initial constellation.\n\nOneWeb's goal was to provide [[Satellite internet constellation|internet services]] to \"everyone, everywhere\" delivering internet connections to rural and remote places as well as to a range of markets.\n\nOneWeb filed for [[bankruptcy]] on 27 March 2020, following a [[liquidity crisis|cash crunch]] amidst difficulties raising capital to complete the build and deployment of the remaining 90% of the network. The company had already laid off approximately 85% of its 531 employees, but said it will maintain satellite operational capabilities while the court restructures it and new owners for the constellation are sought.<ref name=sn20200327/><ref name=wired-bankrupt>{{cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/story/spacex-competitor-oneweb-is-reportedly-bankrupt|title=SpaceX Competitor OneWeb Is Reportedly Bankrupt |date=27 March 2020|access-date=28 March 2020|website=Wired|last=Oberhaus|first=Daniel}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe company was founded in 2012 under the name WorldVu,<ref name=\"prnewswire\"/> based in Britain's [[Channel Islands]].<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://spacenews.com/41755worldvu-a-satellite-startup-aiming-to-provide-global-internet/|title=WorldVu, a Satellite Startup Aiming To Provide Global Internet Connectivity, Continues To Grow Absent Clear Google Relationship|publisher=[[Spacenews.com]]|date=3 September 2014|access-date=15 February 2018|last=de Selding|first=Peter B.}}</ref> \n\nIn 2015, OneWeb secured US$500 million in funding, and agreed to purchase certain future launch services, from existing aerospace industry companies [[Arianespace]] and [[Virgin Galactic]].<ref name=nbc20150625>{{cite news|title=OneWeb Wins US$500 Million in Backing for Internet Satellite Network|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/science/space/oneweb-wins-500-million-backing-internet-satellite-network-n381691|work=NBC News|date=2015-06-25|access-date=2016-02-08|last=Boyle|first=Alan}}</ref><ref name=sn20140530>{{Cite news|title=Google-backed Global Broadband Venture Secures Spectrum for Satellite Network |url=http://spacenews.com/40736google-backed-global-broadband-venture-secures-spectrum-for-satellite/|work=[[SpaceNews]]|date=2014-05-30|access-date=2016-02-08|language=en-US|last=de Selding|first=Peter B.}}</ref> In June 2015, OneWeb also entered into a deal with [[Airbus Defence and Space]] for the construction of its broadband Internet satellites after a competition among U.S. and European manufacturers.<ref>{{Cite web|title=OneWeb selects Airbus to build 900 Internet satellites {{!}} Spaceflight Now|url=http://spaceflightnow.com/2015/06/15/oneweb-selects-airbus-to-build-900-internet-satellites/|access-date=2016-02-08|first=Stephen|last=Clark}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, one year after the initial announcement, OneWeb stated they were on schedule.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spacenews.com/one-year-after-kickoff-oneweb-says-its-700-satellite-constellation-is-on-schedule/|title=One year after kickoff, OneWeb says its 700-satellite constellation is on schedule|date=6 July 2016|last=de Selding|first=Peter B.|access-date=28 March 2020|website=SpaceNews}}</ref> In December 2016, OneWeb raised US$1 billion from [[SoftBank Group|SoftBank Group Corp.]] and US$200 million from existing investors.<ref name=sn201702/><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/oneweb-softbank/softbank-to-invest-1-billion-in-u-s-satellite-venture-oneweb-idUSL4N1EE3I6|title=SoftBank to invest $1 billion in U.S. satellite venture OneWeb|last=Weir |first=Keith|website=Reuters|access-date=2016-12-19}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, OneWeb announced that it expected to sell all of its capacity by launch time, yet the only announced capacity sold was for a joint [[Gogo Inflight Internet|Gogo]] and [[Intelsat]] venture. Wyler announced he was considering nearly quadrupling the size of the satellite constellation by adding 1972 additional satellites that it has priority rights to.<ref name=sn201702>{{cite web |url=https://spacenews.com/oneweb-weighing-2000-more-satellites/|title=OneWeb weighing 2,000 more satellites - SpaceNews.com|date=24 February 2017|publisher=SpaceNews|access-date=23 April 2018|last=Pultarova |first=Tereza}}</ref> With the original capital raise of US$500 million in 2015, plus the US$1 billion investment of SoftBank in 2016, previous \"investors committed to an additional US$200 million, bringing OneWeb's total capital raised to US$1.7 billion\".<ref name=sn201702/> A [[merger]] arrangement with [[Intelsat]] that had been in negotiations during May 2017 collapsed in June and did not go forward.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spacenews.com/oneweb-says-no-steam-lost-despite-intelsat-merger-unravelling/|title=OneWeb says no steam lost despite Intelsat merger unravelling - SpaceNews.com|date=1 June 2017 |publisher=SpaceNews|access-date=23 April 2018|last=Henry|first=Caleb}}</ref>\n\n[[File:OneWeb satellite manufacturing facility, Merritt Island, Florida, 2019 01.jpg|thumb|left|upright=2|OneWeb satellite manufacturing facility in Merritt Island, Florida]]\n\nBy 2019, OneWeb had formed a [[joint venture]] \u2014 '''OneWeb Satellites'''<!-- bolded per [[WP:MOSBOLD]] as a redirect target --> \u2014 with the European company [[Airbus Defence and Space]] in order to manufacturer its satellites in higher volume and at lower cost than any satellites previously built by Airbus. A manufacturing facility was built in [[Merritt Island, Florida]]. Initial satellite production at the new facility began in mid-2019 and by January 2020, the factory reached the target production rate of two satellites per day.<ref name=sn20200206>{{cite news|url=https://spacenews.com/oneweb-plans-april-launch-break-to-tweak-satellite-design/|title=OneWeb plans April launch break to tweak satellite design|work=[[SpaceNews]]|last=Henry|first=Caleb|date=6 February 2020|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 February 2019, OneWeb successfully launched its first six satellites into low Earth orbit from the [[Centre Spatial Guyanais]] in [[French Guiana]] using a [[Soyuz-2]] rocket.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.oneweb.world/newsroom/oneweb-makes-history-as-first-launch-mission-is-a-success|title=OneWeb makes history as first launch mission is a success|date=2019-02-28|work=OneWeb|access-date=2019-02-28|language=en|archive-date=15 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190515095707/https://www.oneweb.world/newsroom/oneweb-makes-history-as-first-launch-mission-is-a-success|url-status=dead}}</ref> The same day OneWeb announced that it signed its first two client agreements marking the beginning of its commercialization.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oneweb.world/newsroom/oneweb-announces-first-two-client-agreements-start-of-commercial-network-commercialisation|title=OneWeb Announces First Two Client Agreements - Start of Commercial Network Commercialisation|date=2019-02-27|work=OneWeb |access-date=2019-02-27|language=en|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512165012/https://www.oneweb.world/newsroom/oneweb-announces-first-two-client-agreements-start-of-commercial-network-commercialisation|archive-date=12 May 2019}}</ref> On 18 March 2019, OneWeb announced it had secured $1.25 billion in funding following a successful first launch. The funding was from existing investors SoftBank and Qualcomm, as well as [[Grupo Salinas]] and the [[Government of Rwanda]].<ref name=bloomberg20190318>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-03-18/oneweb-raises-fresh-1-25-billion-for-internet-system-from-space?|title=OneWeb Raises Fresh $1.25 Billion for Internet System From Space|work=[[Bloomberg News]]|date=18 March 2019|access-date=21 March 2020|last=Vance|first=Ashlee}}</ref>\n\nBy August 2019, the company had 6 of its satellites broadcasting at the right frequencies for 90 days, meeting the \"use-it-or-lose-it\" spectrum conditions set by the [[United Nations]]' [[International Telecommunication Union]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-08-07/oneweb-claims-a-win-in-internet-space-race-with-musk-and-bezos?srnd=markets-vp|title=OneWeb Claims a Win in Internet Space Race Against Musk and Bezos|last=Seal|first=Thomas|date=7 August 2019|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-12}}</ref> This secured the vital rights OneWeb needed to operate its global satellite broadband network.<ref name=\":1\"/>\n\nIn February and March 2020, the company launched an additional 68 satellites to orbit, stating that it would slow down for a minor design modification to be made before planning to launch again in May.<ref name=sn20200206/>\n\nIn March 2020, during the [[2019\u201320_coronavirus_pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]] and [[2020 stock market crash|market turmoil]], OneWeb found themselves in a [[Liquidity crisis|cash crunch]] and is considering [[bankruptcy|bankruptcy court protection]] even as it is looking for out-of-court alternatives to funding ongoing operations.<ref name=bloomberglaw20200319>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-19/softbank-s-oneweb-is-said-to-mull-bankruptcy-as-cash-dwindles|title= SoftBank's OneWeb to Consider Bankruptcy as Cash Dwindles|work=Bloomberg Technology|last=Ronalds-Hannon|first=Eliza|date=19 March 2020|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> By the time of the bankruptcy filing, the company had reduced its workforce from 531 employees down to 74.<ref>{{cite web|title=Motion to Authorize / Debtors' Motion for (A) Interim and Final Authority to (I) Pay Prepetition Wages, Salaries, and Other Compensation and Benefits, (II) Maintain Employee Benefit Programs, and (B) Certain Related Relief filed by Dennis F. Dunne on behalf of OneWeb Global Limited|url=https://www.bankruptcyobserver.com/document/ONEWEB-GLOBAL/9|work=BankruptcyObserver.com |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The effect on the previously planned ten launches in 2020 was not publicly discussed.<ref name=ars20200323>{{cite news|url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2020/03/oneweb-launches-new-satellites-amid-questions-about-its-fiscal-health/|title=OneWeb Says It Will Have To Cut Workers Amid Economic Crisis|work=Ars technica|last=Berger|first=Eric|date=23 March 2020|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn March 27, 2020, OneWeb Global Limited and 18 affiliates all filed bankruptcy in the [[United States Bankruptcy Court for the Southern District of New York]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://spaceflightnow.com/2020/03/30/oneweb-files-for-bankruptcy/|date=30 March 2020|last=Clark|first=Stephen|access-date=30 March 2020|work=Spaceflight Now|title=OneWeb files for bankruptcy}}</ref><ref name=bankobs20200327/><ref name=wired-bankrupt/> The company blamed the [[2019\u201320_coronavirus_pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]], but they need to raise an additional several billion dollars of capital after development and early testing was always a part of the plan, and the high-cost structure of OneWeb's [[Space launch market competition|contracted launches]] and satellites relative to the market size and other emerging competition had been known for some time, and was thought to be challenging well prior to the emergence of the pandemic.<ref name=sn20200327>{{cite news|url=https://spacenews.com/oneweb-files-for-chapter-11-bankruptcy/|title=OneWeb files for Chapter 11 bankruptcy|work=[[SpaceNews]]|last=Henry|first=Caleb|date=27 March 2020|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> The primary case is identified as case number 20-22437.<ref name=bankobs20200327>{{cite web|title=Bankruptcy of OneWeb Global Limited|url=https://www.bankruptcyobserver.com/bankruptcy-case/ONEWEB-GLOBAL|work=BankruptcyObserver.com|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> OneWeb Satellites, the joint venture between OneWeb and Airbus Defence to build the satellites, says they have done temporary furloughs due to the Coronavirus pandemic but that they are not due to the OneWeb bankruptcy filing.<ref>{{cite tweet |last=Foust |first=Jeff|author-link=Jeff Foust |user=jeff_foust |number=1244632083689078785 |date=30 March 2020 |title=OneWeb Satellites... has implemented 'temporary furloughs' of staff, but says that is due to COVID-19 and not OneWeb's Ch. 11 bankruptcy filing. |access-date=30 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Satellites ==\n{{main|OneWeb satellite constellation}}\n[[File:KSC-20170316-PH KLS01 0007~orig.jpg|thumb|Model of a OneWeb satellite]]\nIn 2016, OneWeb planned for a launch cadence of 30-36 satellites a month <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spacenews.com/leo-constellation-operators-oneweb-iridium-announce-collaboration/|title=LEO constellation operators OneWeb, Iridium announce collaboration|date=2019-09-17|website=SpaceNews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-20|last=Henry|first=Caleb}}</ref> to create an initial constellation of 650 satellites. The satellites operate in Low Earth Orbit (LEO). OneWeb chose an altitude of 1200 km for its satellites because there is a minimum existing population of satellites and [[space debris|debris]] at that altitude.<ref name=\":2\"/>\n\nLike existing LEO based communications satellite constellations, OneWeb's satellites are closer to Earth and will, therefore, provide much lower transmission delays than geostationary satellite broadband services<ref name=\":3\"/>. As late as January 2020, OneWeb was still planning to provide 10 times the bandwidth and one-tenth of the latency of existing geostationary satellites.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.computerweekly.com/feature/Norways-autonomous-ships-point-to-new-horizons|title=Norway's autonomous ships point to new horizons|website=ComputerWeekly.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-02 |date=29 May 2019|last=Mathieson|first=SA}}</ref>\n\nOneWeb's factory in Exploration Park on [[Merritt Island, Florida]] opened in July 2019, just outside the gates of NASA's Kennedy Space Center.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://spaceflightnow.com/2020/03/17/soyuz-launch-preps-in-kazakhstan-proceeding-despite-travel-restrictions/|title=Soyuz launch preps in Kazakhstan proceed despite travel restrictions|access-date=18 March 2020|date=17 March 2020|last=Clark|first=Stephen|website=Spaceflight Now}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/orlando/news/2019/07/29/oneweb-satellites-opens-85m-production-facility-in.html|title=OneWeb Satellite Opens 85m Production Facility|last=Saleh|first=Malak|date=29 July 2019|website=Orlando Business Journal|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref> The factory is a joint venture with [[Airbus]] and has a production capacity of two satellites a day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thisismoney.co.uk/money/markets/article-7344829/Adrian-Steckel-rocketman-wholl-launch-34-satellites-MONTH.html|title=Adrian Steckel: The rocketman who'll launch 34 satellites every MONTH|last=Nimmo|first=Jamie|date=2019-08-10|website=Mail Online|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref> The satellites will be programmed to detect the end of their life span after 5-7 years in orbit, and deorbit themselves from space and so that they burn up in the atmosphere as they [[atmospheric reentry|descend towards Earth]].<ref name=\":4\"/>\n\n== Responsible space ==\nIn June 2019, OneWeb rolled out its initiative Responsible Space to outline the specific approaches it plans to take to promote sustainability and safe operations in space.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web |url=https://spacenews.com/can-satellite-megaconstellations-be-responsible-users-of-space/|title=Can satellite megaconstellations be responsible users of space?|date=2019-09-03|website=SpaceNews.com |language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-22|last=Foust|first=Jeff}}</ref> Responsible Space covers design and operational practices, including disposal of a satellite within 5 years of the end of its mission; developing an \"ecosystem\" within the space industry that supports sustainability; and collaboration with other space operators.<ref name=\":2\"/>&nbsp;As one example, OneWeb plans to include a grapple fixture on its satellites so that a third-party satellite could grab it and tug it out of orbit, should the satellite prove non-responsive.<ref name=\":2\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Portal|Spaceflight}}\n* {{Official website|oneweb.world}}\n\n[[Category:Satellite Internet access]]\n[[Category:Communications satellite operators]]\n[[Category:Aerospace companies]]\n[[Category:Satellite telephony]]\n[[Category:2012 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British companies established in 2012]]\n[[Category:British brands]]\n[[Category:Companies based in London]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 2012]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Arlington County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Companies that filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy in 2020]]\n", "name_user": "Yarnalgo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSatellites:image above {{main}}", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OneWeb"}
